<br>
So, in other words, you don’t know. I’ll see your bet and raise you that those scientists at NASA looked over the studies and realized the very obvious – nuclear detonations cause a lot of damage. I think those boys who developed Orion were so overwhelmed with the concept; they ignored the effects of nuclear detonations. The guys at NASA weren’t so easily fooled.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The following is the full text of a radio interview with George Dyson and Dr. Freeman Dyson (ostensibly to promote the book) conducted on 6/21/02 on NPR radio.<br>
<br>
It's from a subscriber-only pay site so, rather than just put up a link that would require anyone to subscribe, I'm quoting it in full, here...<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Interview: Freeman Dyson and George Dyson discuss Project Orion <br>
<br>
Date: 06/21/2002; Publication: Talk of the Nation Science Friday (NPR); Author: IRA FLATOW <br>
<br>
Interview: Freeman Dyson and George Dyson discuss Project Orion Host: IRA FLATOW Time: 3:00-4:00 PM <br>
<br>
IRA FLATOW, host: <br>
Welcome back to TALK OF THE NATION/SCIENCE FRIDAY. I'm Ira Flatow. <br>
<br>
The next part of the hour we're going to talk about something totally different. You know, talked to a lot of astronauts over the years, and when you ask an astronaut what it feels like to sit atop a big tank of liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen, coupled to some--maybe some solid rocket boosters, too, and then light it off, they'll tell you it's a big unnerving. In fact, they used to say that the Saturn 5 rocket was the biggest conventional weapon ever made, considering all the rocket fuel that was there. <br>
<br>
OK, you got that picture? Now instead of that, think of that--what if I told you you were going to be sitting on top of a whole bunch of nuclear bombs, and that exploding these bombs outside the rocket would give you the propulsive force to get where you need to go? Sounds fantastic? Well, that's the basic idea behind an old proposal from the 1950s for a faster way of getting to space, a way of overcoming some of the problems with current rocket technology. It was called Project Orion, and though it might sound pretty unbelievable today, at its peak dozens of some of the world's brightest scientists were on that team. <br>
<br>
And one of them is with me now, Dr. Freeman Dyson; also joining me is his son George Dyson, who has written a book about the project and how it came to be. The book is called &quot;Project Orion: The True Story of the Atomic Spacecraft.&quot; And it's just being published by Henry Holt. And if you'd like to talk about it with us, give us a call. Our number is 1 (800) 989-8255; 1 (800) 989-TALK. And surf over to our Web site at sciencefriday.com where you can find out more about the project. <br>
<br>
Let me formally introduce my guests. George Dyson is the author of the book &quot;Project Orion: The True Story of the Atomic Spaceship,&quot; out from Henry Holt. He joins us from the studios of KUOW in Seattle. <br>
<br>
Welcome to the program. <br>
<br>
Mr. GEORGE DYSON (Author, &quot;Project Orion&quot; ) : Thank you. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: You're welcome. And Dr. Freeman Dyson, who is a legend in his own time, actually--he knew and worked with such luminaries as Edward Teller, Ted Taylor, Robert Oppenheimer, Richard Feynman and was at the Institute of Advanced Study when Albert Einstein was walking those halls. And he was one of the members of the Orion-Project team and he is still there, a professor of physics at the institute in Princeton. <br>
<br>
Thank you for being with us, Dr. Dyson. <br>
<br>
Dr. FREEMAN DYSON (Participant, Project Orion): Hello. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Hi there. Describe the ship for us, so we can get a general picture of what it looked like on the drawing board. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: So it wasn't like a rocket at all. It was like a round, 15-story building, about 100 feet in diameter and about 200 feet high. So think of it as a ship rather than as a rocket.<br>
 <br>
FLATOW: And give us an idea how--you know, people think, well, we have nuclear explosions; isn't that going to blow up the ship? What' s the theory behind its operation? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, the theory is that each explosion lasts only a very, very short time, so the bottom of the ship is a big, flat plate and it takes the force of the explosions, but it's in contact with the hot gas only for a very, very short time, less than a thousandth of a second, so it doesn't have time to get very hot. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: So there would be a mechanism of dropping out these little nuclear bombs below the ship... <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: ...and that would push it up? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: They're not so little. These are regular, more or less full-size bombs, and you have to have a big gun to shoot them out and they have to be shot out at the rate of about two a second. So it's a big engineering problem. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: And how many bombs are we talking about that it would take to get you, let's say, to the moon or to Mars? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, we thought of about 1,000 to the moon and back, and about 2,000 to Mars and back, maybe give or take a few hundred. With 2,000 you could also go to Jupiter or to Saturn. Essentially, you're free all over the solar system once you get away from the Earth. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: And you had a schedule you were working on, correct? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Right. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: What schedule--you wanted to get to Saturn by when? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: 1970 was our schedule for Saturn, but we thought we would be at Mars by 1965 and Saturn by 1970. That was our slogan. Of course, that would all depend on everything going according to plan and getting the funding, which never happened. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Never happened. Let me bring in George Dyson. Let's talk about the background of this project. Where did it come from? <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: The idea or the funding? <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Both of them. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Well, the idea really goes back to Stan Ulam, who was one of the Los Alamos mathematical physicists, who right--watching basically the first explosion, the Trinity test, he had the idea that this would be a good way to go into space. And so then the whole question is how do you translate that energy into moving a ship. And the funding came right after the Russian Sputnik went up from ARPA, the Advanced Research Products Agency, now DARPA, and they put in the first million dollars, which was actually a check for 999,750 because they didn't want to go over a million-dollar limit and have to sort of ask the grown-ups for permission. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: So how much of this was a desire on the part of people like Edward Teller, who is considered the father of the H-bomb, and others to make something constructive, rather than destructive, out of a nuclear weapon? <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Well, I think--Freeman was there, so... <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Freeman. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: ...he knows better than I do, but... <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yeah. Teller wasn't involved, in fact, except just as a friend. He didn't take any part in the project. No, we all had that feeling that... <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Yeah. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: ...this was a wonderful way of getting rid of the bombs and not hurting anybody, that the whole idea was to get rid of the bombs and do something useful at the same time. So it was very attractive to people who'd only been working on the military uses of bombs. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: And so what went wrong? I mean, why don't we have one today? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, a lot of things went wrong, mostly contamination. Unfortunately, the bombs are highly radioactive and they leave a lot of fallout behind. So if you exploded a few hundred of these bombs in the atmosphere, it would give fallout all over the world, and that became more and more unpopular as time went on. And I think that was a very sufficient reason for not doing it. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: George. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Well, that's certainly true, that there was--there turned out to be no way to do a clean Orion. At the beginning, the hope was that we would develop clean bombs that would make the thing sort of, you know, two orders of magnitude cleaner, a hundred times cleaner. And then, I think, it might have been acceptable. It also might have been acceptable if it had turned out that the Russians were doing the same thing, and instead of sort of the race to the moon that we did have, we might have had a race to Jupiter or Saturn, and then I think the political climate would have been very different. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Freeman, why is this a better way of getting where we're going, this idea? Let's say there was a clean method of doing it. Physically speaking, on the physics, why is this a better way than using the rockets we have now? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, because the rockets don't take you any further than the moon. We haven't gone any further than the moon since 1969, when we first got there. The shuttle never goes further than low Earth orbits and, of course, the International Space Station isn't going anywhere. There is no chemical rocket system for taking people further than the moon. It's just extraordinarily difficult, whereas with a nuclear propulsion, you have so much more energy and so much less weight that you can really go places. That's the big difference. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Now why isn't the bomb--explain a little bit again. Why doesn't the bomb explode the rocket ship itself? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, of course, the reason is that the rocket ship is built very strong and rugged. It's more like a submarine than like an airplane. It's made of thick metal and the bottom of it is particularly tough. That's where the explosion is actually taken. And then, of course, there is a lot of careful design. You have to have shock absorbers separating this bottom plate from the rest of the ship, and you have to be very careful that you don't just break everything up the first time you blow off the bomb. And, of course, we never actually tried it out to make sure, but we did have pretty good confidence it would work. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: And how far was the bomb from the ship when it exploded? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: About a hundred feet. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: A hundred feet. And why didn't it melt the bottom of the ship? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Because it wasn't there long enough. The explosions are so quick that the heat doesn't have time to penetrate. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Did this take technology that is still classified information? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes, to some extent. A lot of it could be declassified, but most of it still remains secret, either just for bureaucratic reasons or for two reasons. We certainly don't want to give away the detailed design of small bombs. That's something that can be very useful to terrorists, so that should be kept secret. On the other hand, the general dimensions and performance of the ship would not be of any use to terrorists, and there's no reason why that shouldn' t be declassified. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. In fact, George, you write in the book on page 57 about Ted Taylor, one of the fathers of this project, that Ted--well, I'll read it from the book. `Ted was the first to raise the alarm. The use of small numbers of covertly delivered nuclear explosives by groups of people who are not clearly identified with national government is more probable in the near future than the use of nuclear weapons by a nation for military purposes.' I mean, you say he warned us in 1966. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Right. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Yeah. He wrote an extremely prophetic paper actually warning that the real danger might not be foreign groups but might be groups within the United States who somehow felt they were trying to save us from something worse. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Freeman. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: You write also that if you have a bunch--I'm going to read from the book--`If you have a bunch of people wanting to blow up the World Trade Center or something, they might have no difficulty getting large amounts of high explosives, so it's important not to declassify all that stuff.' <br>
Did you write this before the attack or after the attack on the World Trade Center? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: I don't remember when I wrote that, but I've certainly been saying that for a long time. It was obvious that the World Trade Center was a prime target, and we certainly--for many, many years we were worrying about a smuggled nuclear weapon destroying the World Trade Center. That's still, of course, a very real problem for all the other skyscrapers. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: 1 (800) 989-8255. You know, you have a--there was a phrase that was coined about you--I'm sure--I know you're familiar with, about innovative, interesting ideas called `Dysonian.' If there's something really interesting, an unusual idea, they call it a Dysonian idea. Would you consider this a Dysonian idea, or something a little more conventional? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: No. I don't claim credit for that. I think Ted Taylor was worrying about this even before I was. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Well, so, what about the fact that we've not gone anywhere past the moon? How do you feel about that now? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, I'm sad, of course. I wish we had gone further. And there are other ways of getting there which don't involve nuclear explosions, so I certainly don't want to revive Orion today. But I would like to start out with other means of propulsion, like laser propulsion, which could get us there much more efficiently than chemicals. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. But we don't seem to have the national will to do that now, to spend that kind of money, do we? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, it doesn't require huge amounts of money. It does require long-range planning and thinking. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. 1 (800) 989-8255. George, what would you think is the lesson of the Orion-Project here? <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Well, just to not lose our imagination. Look at the imagination we had. This was right after World War II, and, you know, we were gonna let these guys take off with 2,600 nuclear bombs. And now you can't fly with a Swiss Army knife. We're just being--I think that' s the message is to not give up those kinds of dreams. You would never want to do it that way but, like my father says, there's other ways to do it. And let's think beyond the moon and, you know, keep looking at what we could do. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: You know, it's hard for people who were not around in the '50s to recall how excited everybody was about nuclear power, nuclear energy, nuclear bombs. I remember people would say that nuclear power is going to be so cheap that no one's going to have a meter on their electricity. I mean, things that they were talking about--making a nuclear airplane, weren't they? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yeah. The nuclear airplane was probably the silliest of all those things. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: And why is that? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, because it would have been so--the nuclear reactor is just so heavy that it would not have been possible to shield it. So it's hard to see how it could have been useful. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Do you think that if the Russians had been building something similar that your program might have kept going? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. I think that's very likely. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: So we need that political kick. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Oh, yes. It's always good to have an enemy. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: And we don't have one today to get--we don't have... <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: We do, but not the right kind. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Not the one that's going to Mars. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Right. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: 1 (800) 989-8255 is our number. Let's see--to go to Gary in Seattle. Hi, Gary. <br>
<br>
GARY (Caller): Hello. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Hi, there. <br>
<br>
GARY: I've long been an admirer of the Orion-Project, and I want to say to George I read his previous book, which was a great book. I want to ask Dr. Dyson, though, in relation to Orion, and supposing like a recent movie &quot;Deep Impact&quot; where we had a nasty comet heading our way and we had to go out there and get it, isn't the Orion the only one--I believe they used that in the movie--the only type of propulsion unit that would get us out there with the amount of sufficient power and the proper time to help, you know, divert a comet? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: I don't think that's true, but I haven't done the calculations. I think, in fact, it would take us so long to get an Orion ship built and launch, we'd do much better just with mass-produced chemical rockets of the kind we already have. But I haven't done the calculations. But I would guess you'd probably do better using conventional means if you have to do something fast. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Thanks for calling. <br>
<br>
GARY: Yes. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: 1 (800) 989-8255 is our number. I'm talking with Freeman Dyson and George Dyson this hour about Project Orion on TALK OF THE NATION/SCIENCE FRIDAY from NPR News. <br>
George, you write in your book that when you tried to interest <br>
George Kistiakowsky--well, not you, but these scientists--President Eisenhower' s science adviser, quote, &quot;his reception of this was not enthusiastic.&quot; What happened to change all that? <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Well, nobody really high up was enthusiastic about this project because of the political liability. I mean, it--nothing this ambitious could be developed without, obviously, some kind of failure or accident along the way, and that was politically very difficult. So it was the lower-level people, particularly within the Air Force, not within NAS--few within NASA, who supported it very strongly and kept it alive. But they could never really get the top-level political go-ahead. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: So did they feel that there was a military side of this that- -of course, another spinoff? <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: I don't think anybody really believed in, you know, an immediate military application other than sort of the general view that if we controlled deep space it would, you know, help some sort of domination over Earth. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: But for the Air Force to keep funding the project they had to have military justification. So some very imaginative sort of, you know, what today would be PowerPoint presentations, were given to, you know, the generals in Washington as to why we should do this. But those ideas were never supported at the secretary of Defense level. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Freeman, I went through a list of some of the luminaries of physics who you've worked with over the years. Who would you say was the most exciting person to work with? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Oh, Feynman, by all means. But I didn't really work with him, but I just was a friend and loved to listen to him talk. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. You took a very interesting bus ride that resulted in an epiphany for you, didn't it? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Right. He was, of course, a professor when I was a student, so I learned a tremendous lot from him. And then afterwards, I acted as his interpreter to make his wild ideas more accessible to ordinary people. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: And what was the problem you helped solve? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, I wouldn't say I helped solve the problem, but Feynman already had solved the problem but in a way that only he could understand. And I made it more intelligible and just sort of tidied up the details. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Now you came from sort of a different school from the European school of physics and math as opposed to the American school, didn' t you? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: That was true. And, of course, the European school was generally more mathematical and more abstract. Americans were more imaginative. And so I happened to be in the right place at the right time. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: So you were sort of able to put into numbers what they were trying--the ideas they were trying to express. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. That was true of Feynman anyway. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. And what was he like to work with? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Oh, wonderful. I mean, he wasn't easy. He would tell you to go to hell if he wasn't wanting to listen what you had to say. He could be very abrupt. On the other hand, when he did listen, you knew that he really was interested, so I found that delightful. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. And when you got to the Institute for Advanced Study, what was that like? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Oh, great fun. Of course, we were all young people who had survived the war, and so we were--it was a very upbeat period. So for those of us who had survived, we were determined to enjoy life and we did. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: All right. We're going to come back and talk lots more with Freeman Dyson and George Dyson, author of &quot;Project Orion: A True Story of the Atomic Spaceship.&quot; Take a lot more of your questions, so don't go away. We'll be right back after this break. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: I'm Ira Flatow, and this is TALK OF THE <br>
<br>
NATION/SCIENCE FRIDAY from NPR News. <br>
(Announcements) <br>
<br>
FLATOW: You're listening to TALK OF THE NATION/SCIENCE FRIDAY. I' m Ira Flatow. <br>
A brief program note: On Monday's TALK OF THE NATION, Neal Conan talks with parents and teens about sex. <br>
We're talking this hour about the Orion-Project with Freeman Dyson and George Dyson. Our number: 1 (800) 989-8255. Let's go to the phones and see what's on the minds of other folks. Hi, Mike in Indianapolis. Hi. Welcome to SCIENCE FRIDAY. <br>
<br>
MIKE (Caller): How you doing, Ira? <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Hi. Go ahead. <br>
<br>
MIKE: Well, my question is why would you not build this ship in space, thereby overcoming the problem of the dirty bombs in the atmosphere? <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Freeman. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: It's just too expensive to do that. Of course, we thought of it, of course, right at the beginning. But the cost of getting the ship up using conventional rockets turned out to be much, much larger than the cost of building it on the ground, so you'd lose all the advantage of doing it cheaply. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. How--compare this... <br>
<br>
MIKE: Well, let me ask you this... <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Compare--I'm sorry. Go ahead. <br>
<br>
MIKE: Are you there? <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Yeah. Go ahead. <br>
<br>
MIKE: Yeah. Would the advantage of a long-distance trip--would the overall efficiency--wouldn't that overcome the disadvantage of initially getting the material in space? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: No. It turns out not to. <br>
<br>
MIKE: OK. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: The whole point of Orion was that it gets you off the ground cheaply, which you can't do any other way. <br>
<br>
MIKE: OK. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: All right, Mike. Thanks for calling. <br>
<br>
MIKE: You bet. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: 1 (800) 989-8255 is our number if you'd like to talk to Freeman or George Dyson about this strange, strange rocket ship that--Patrick. Is it Mantega, California? <br>
<br>
PATRICK (Caller): Manteca. Yeah. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Manteca. I'm sorry. Go ahead. <br>
<br>
PATRICK: I was wondering, so say you could cleanly get it up into space... <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Right. <br>
<br>
PATRICK: ...how would you protect the crew from the radiation if you dropped the bomb down? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, the bombs are only being fired for a few minutes, so during the time the bombs are firing the crew would be hiding in a little shelter on board the ship, so they would have additional shielding apart from the shielding around the whole ship. The other thing, of course, is just that the debris from the bomb doesn't stick to the ship. It simply flies away into space, so not very much gets into the ship. What does get in turns out to be quite within the regular limits. But the essential point is that the ship is big enough so that shielding is quite cheap. If you tried to make an Orion small, then the shielding problem becomes impossible, but the bigger it is the easier it is to shield and the less problem you have with radiation. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Give us an idea and compare it to the shuttle today how much bigger it would be. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: It's--well, it weighs about 200 times as much, and the actual--I don't know how much it is in actual size. It's certainly about probably a hundred times the size of the shuttle in volume. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: This is a big ship, George. It would carry a lot of people- -aimed to carry a lot of people? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yeah. We... <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Yeah, the important... <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Go ahead. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: The important thing, it's not only bigger but three-quarters of it is payload instead of something like the shuttle where only a very small fraction is usable payload. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Freeman, you say that the bombs would not be firing all the time. When would they? At what portion of the voyage? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, the main problem is getting off the ground, so you' d be firing for about five minutes to get yourself from the ground into space and maybe another five minutes to get up enough speed to go to Mars. And then after that you are cruising then for months without any bombs at all. Then when you arrive at Mars you would explode some more bombs for a couple of minutes. So it's very short spells in which the bombs are firing. In that way it's just like a chemical rocket. In between you're just cruising, and then you can come out of your shelter and roam around the ship as much as you want, or outside. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Did anybody do research? I mean, there was so much effort devoted to building this ship, did anybody talk about the living accommodations and the food and things like that inside? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. Oh, we had everything rather detailed. It was quite luxurious compared with the shuttle because the people were expected to be there for several years. So we planned to have a library and an exercise room and all the other things you would need, like a hotel. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Interesting. Let's go to Val, in Chester, New Jersey. Hi, Val. <br>
<br>
VAL (Caller): Hi. My question is the rate of acceleration that the ship would feel. It must accelerate much faster than a chemical rocket. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: No. Actually not. It turned out that the acceleration was probably two or three G's, which is much less than you get in the shuttle. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: OK. <br>
<br>
VAL: But is it--but it was sustained over a longer period of time? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. A few minutes longer, but not very much longer. But it turns out that just because the yield of the bombs are adjustable, there's no reason to go to a high acceleration. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Thanks for calling, Val. <br>
<br>
VAL: Thank you. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Did you have to design a new kind of bomb specifically for this project, because, you know, back in the '50s we hear about these giant megaton, you know, bombs that were being built. Did you have to learn how to make a smaller bomb for that? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, they wouldn't have been smaller. Actually, they were quite large. You wanted to have a lot of debris to hit the bottom of the ship, so there was no advantage in making them very small. But we wanted to economize on plutonium, and so we wanted to make bombs that would work with small amounts of plutonium but still have pretty high yields. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. George, let's talk about writing this book. This book is so chock full of facts and places and names, very well-documented. How were you--did you have to get some of this stuff declassified? <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Yeah. I was able to get--the Air Force was very helpful with declassifying what they could. This was sort of just before the bureaucratic doors slammed shut with the sort of Wen Ho Lee business. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: But mainly I was just driven by this insatiable curiosity. If you can imagine being five years old, which was 44 years ago, when Freeman, my father, could first tell me that, you know, we were moving to California and he was going to help build this spaceship and go to Mars in a few more years, but he couldn't tell me any more than that. He said it was secret and someday he hoped I would find out. So now I realize that the people like Ted that he worked with were getting old, and I'd better find out now or it'd be too late, so that' s what I did. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: I don't ever remember hearing about this spaceship until, I mean, you wrote about it. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Well, it was... <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Was it well-known? You said it was secret... <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: It was... <br>
<br>
FLATOW: ...to begin with, but... <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: At first it was completely secret. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Yeah. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Not even the name Orion could be mentioned or what it was at all. And then they were able to talk about--the general idea of the thing was fairly well-known, but the details are still secret. And so it's--you know, it was very hard to get the old-timers to freely talk about it. That was quite a job. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Freeman, is there any talking among the old-timers about those days besides books like your son's? I mean, is there any recollection of oral history that are being done? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, of course. George has collected much more than I'd known about. But if you want to hear about it, you have to read the book. There's no doubt there's no substitute for that. But of course, we have been--the people involved have been talking about it, and we all have this very happy memory of a great time when we were young and enthusiastic; we really had a go at it. It was a grand dream, and we still treasure that. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. Let's go back to the phones. Joe, in Pembroke Pines, Florida. Hi, Joe. <br>
<br>
JOE (Caller): Yes. Hi. I'd like to know once the rocket completed its mission, what type of recovery would happen once it entered into the Earth's atmosphere? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, we would probably have left the ship in orbit around the Earth so it could be used again, and then come down in an ordinary rocket or capsule the same way the astronauts did when they came back from the moon. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: All right, Joe. Thanks for calling. <br>
<br>
JOE: You're welcome. Thank you. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Freeman, how would you compare the problems in physics that physicists were talking about in those days compared to what we're talking about now with string theory and supersymmetry and things like that? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, it wasn't really physics; it was engineering. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: It's certainly totally different from string theory. But what the main difference, of course, is that in those days we didn't have cheap computers. We had some kind of computers, but they were very expensive, so almost all our calculations were done just by hand with hand calculators. And nowadays, of course, you'd do the whole job on a supercomputer, much more accurately. So if we went over it again today we would be able to predict with much more confidence whether it would work or not. I think that's the main difference. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: How well did you know Albert Einstein at the institute? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Not at all. He was there, but he wasn't interested in what the young people were doing, so we were too shy to go and say hello. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Let me remind everybody I'm Ira Flatow, and this is <br>
TALK OF THE NATION/SCIENCE FRIDAY from NPR News. <br>
So you avoided him and he avoided you. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. It was unfortunate, but that's the way it was. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Let's see if we can go to the phones and go to Dave in Alameda, California. Hi, Dave. <br>
<br>
DAVE (Caller): Hi. I was hoping you guys could comment on the work that was done at the Nevada Test Site(ph) from 1950 through 1970 to develop nuclear reactors for space travel. Is Orion the same type of project or an offshoot? And... <br>
Dr. DYSON: No. It's quite separate. There was a different project called Rova, which was using a nuclear reactor as a rocket. But there was a test done--well, a whole lot of tests--in Nevada. I saw that rocket sitting there. It was a very different system. It didn't have anything like the performance of Orion. On the other hand, it also didn't have so much political difficulties. But it also got stopped by the same kind of bureaucratic difficulties that Orion got into. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: But you helped design--What?--the most successful nuclear reactor still in it... <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yeah. That was nothing to do with space. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Right. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: That was a reactor that's mostly used in hospitals for making short-lived isotopes for diagnosing and treating cancers. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: What is that called? TRIGGA(ph)? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: How much money did you make on that one? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: $1. I got--well, of course, I was paid as a consultant and I--according to the contract the company picked up the patent for $1, and they did very well with it. <br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. What would you say the biggest challenge facing us today is? If you were to work on a new project, what would you like to work on? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Well, of course, there are two different questions. The biggest challenge, of course, is getting rid of nuclear weapons and making sure that they're not used. That's not--that's not a project; that's a political problem. I would love, of course--I'd love to be involved with a space science project, but nowadays you don't do that with people; you do that with instruments. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. And how do we--do you see any way of getting rid of all these nuclear weapons? <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Yes. I think we can, but it has to--'cause it's a slow process and it has to involve trust. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: So it's a main--the main problem is, of course, opening up communications with all of the people we consider to be possible enemies and beginning to understand what's going on and finally coming to agreements. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Mm-hmm. George, you think Project Orion will ever be used someplace? <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: I don't think so, but I think, you know, that some far- off future when we do go into space and there are missions to Jupiter and that sort of thing, you know, I hope somebody will be on board, you know, reading about it and remembering that these guys were first and they were really planning to go. You know, there's the asteroid threat scenario where something like this might have to be done, but, you know, that's a microscopically thin chance. But it's worth remembering how to, you know, build the thing in case, for some reason, we had to. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: Yeah, and it's made to move a lot of people at once, right? Yeah. <br>
All right. Thank you both for joining me this hour. Freeman Dyson, one of the members of the Orion-Project team and professor of physics at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, and George Dyson, author of the book &quot;Project Orion: The True Story of the Atomic Spaceship,&quot; out from Henry Holt. Thank you both for joining me this hour. <br>
<br>
Dr. DYSON: Thank you. <br>
<br>
Mr. DYSON: Thank you very much. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: You're welcome. <br>
<br>
FLATOW: If you have comments or questions, or you missed any of the topics we talk about, you want to learn more about them, surf over to our Web site at sciencefriday.com. You'll find links to our topics and also archival versions of SCIENCE FRIDAY and also more learning materials. Or you can send us a letter to TALK OF THE NATION/SCIENCE FRIDAY, WNYC Radio, One Centre Street, New York, New York 10007. And you can also send us e-mail at scifri@npr.org. <br>
I'm Ira Flatow. Have a great weekend. We'll see you next week. I'm Ira Flatow in New York. <br>
<br>
