<br>
I already mentioned this, but since it was missed, I will repeat myself.<br>
<br>
There was an interview of Dr. Finger in the December 2002 issue of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Nuclear News</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, who was one of the people responible for reviewing the ORION project and advising his superiors at NASA as to whether to pick up the project. The interviewer asked Finger about ORION and he told him that he thought the people working on it were brilliant individuals, and that the reason he advised NASA not to take up the project was based on worries related to develop a working engine using the ground testing methods traditionaly used by NASA, and the political problems of NASA ground testing nuclear devices. It was not dropped because of fears that the concept would not work.<br>
